[recv] {"type": "message_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Evaluating test coverage and improvements**\n\nI can mention that some test exercises related to the API and serialization fallback are tied to pre-1.2.15 compatibility, which isn't achievable with the current artifact. The user is asking for improvements, not necessarily everything. I should be transparent and perhaps say, \"Added... covers Method#invoke path\" without running tests as instructed. The user expects full test coverage, so I might consider alternative methods or substitutions for triggering fallback. I'll need to deeply assess how to address all uncovered call sites.\n\n**Exploring active class coverage**\n\nThe task runner is asking for active class coverage, and so far, attempts have resulted in zero coverage. It might accept partial coverage, though! I wonder if we could create a test that covers the fallback by constructing an instance via serialization, avoiding test reflection. I should check if a final field can be null due to a constructor exception. Running under a SecurityManager just for the constructor could be an interesting way to approach this!\n\n**Considering JVM instrumentation**\n\nI’m thinking about JVM with an agent and how it maps call sites from loaded classes when the bytecode is identical. But wait, what happens if the classes are loaded from a source context and not from the classpath with reload4j jar? I wonder how instrumentation sees that situation. It seems that the native approach won’t allow for building dynamic classes. Looks like I have a few things to clarify for better understanding!\n\n**Clarifying class dynamics**\n\nI’m considering importing PropertiesPatternConverter, and I wonder if it’s a dynamic class since it doesn’t seem to have dynamic call sites—just calls. It looks like it doesn’t lead directly to an active class. I’m thinking about one-to-one mapping: if I’m targeting MDCKeySetExtractor, I should ensure that any tests cover it directly or indirectly. Should I just use both options? That seems like a good plan!\n\n**Inspecting MDC properties**\n\nI'm thinking about the `event.getMDC(item.toString())` call and whether it properly checks `mdcCopy` first. I wonder if there could be an issue with the assert order in this context. It feels important to dig into this a bit further to clarify what happens in the mapping of properties. I'll need to take a closer look at the implementation to ensure everything is functioning correctly.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_0643568f61f4f3c9016a110bfcfebc8191a8d9a493b9a6a848\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqEQwcAOgPeISVxz6YyDK3biH3XzfP1unj-nasKggXqQLs2GK-RddSoBhOwf6Ht5hNvuRFYIMv-JaR8eyTQtQ0Cymof5dl8Su5EF_45bKolwqrbtv_hkbh-VVR1-ATe-CFlnAgT6S8I4X4bOulQMyZXM8sIp7fe6Snzvd7KjgE5B-kmtT7YxB1--_7rOTB5-opfGWI0LvrZPixwYrtmFa_r_KfpBeuFHwBqXFksV1N3pCnCo2UyGNRW2G04pMkW4z4V2RuNtlcgh5bJcwGl9QCqrmDoTxP3ECwYgj2yWfIH-jDpeuLfNfuNM2LzLTlihJw4SOB6DtQzbiWWFjVC7SRmbIoSkqIP6n49oChTJXFA-oyQfO4SJkZCIXK5TlYx2iyVJb71Ip2JTEKUlZNUx2OzjIdPRK2WjfaxZpxqroY1aeEfFxmvcS1acXUAQYKFnQOgpfJ1rhLudua6T8RutEbjnxMuign91CDSptfEdL3_K3TSt6kr6pO7eVh9RyTaXNVjd1i7UE-K2hxRhc-oK4e947tm6kCBoHTmqTNZ98d62Lq8D2HL1JdGm8fb27BIMYXnd-OwBjWHlWNPQiVETJPJ-hCNRk_vOj6ZRnph8Eowj828eQJWjAtmstZfkPZEvjcjZSPV_AOpnq4N370brsawbCLo3QePhNXrWfkKo3smHSs9Z5hh-kTVz63grFJYFbV_5rYAhQrf0t4d8S146TNw__FVK6Gxo187phAspHl5FE6A4TFfMDGsmXCfmCfjjQJWg8auYo0SxF1z4JPLwb1hH8jDJZi6HHl4inz8-aYVK4AsOCiXeBNAF1vXvBw-2JueCgbSvPvN0F3sgaZS6XIvJ-rDqTDIInQ2Ud5scFxoM0tJNB-aIfQFWY0EH10gcTWt_zfTs_EoZEghQMyaRTGg6d0LmExw-lgomNe4dXh9Ftsfc-WEGLhkfPz2EDuzOCuxPV7sfoRuFz6uCAoHL6YI8xa70cQWpHFoJKwaGtc8xiA23lj8SEqphfPDHeTJpgpAp09udl5OoYikpUCwy4Dr202dJxi3g7_bTPOCOYE-mdrqNuja59Zui4U53SVTHO_AHC5Fdw3UK6N8OAH9BlF46O-udbV3lD7UvaENvYC1Q-JYEq75Db1HJ6mYs-OO7xXDQWDTihyLpuxQAM94DNCPTSaXmLQtK3oCFuwg5r6iHA_6LW5Lb6dhzwIUqPE3VLkL5W4MbzdfJGGugz6mnUZ7jrzaHWCRmlY8-lxXfykDcVQcsfLnreIlFCbPCyOOdwQIimS1n3cIPAgjjzjQKKYU8A6DXWXk6D